     :schema-version "1.0"
     :entry-provenance "authored"
     :required-fields-present #t
     :entry-summary "Stop a playing handle. Idempotent. Descriptor return in REPL."))

(verb
  :name "audio/play"
  :library "audio"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(audio/play source [opts]) -> [status info] | handle"
  :summary "Trigger sound playback; returns a handle you can pass to audio/halt or a pending-audio tuple in headless REPL."
  :impl-status "wired-pending"
  :explanation "audio/play is the primary sound-trigger verb. Give it a resource identifier (a symbol or string naming a pre-loaded sound) and optional keyword args (:volume :loop :rate). Under a live host it returns a playback handle. Under the standalone REPL it returns [pending-audio {source opts}] — the shape a host consumes. Handles are opaque; use them only to pass to audio/halt. Multiple calls queue independent playbacks — audio/play does NOT restart a running stream, it layers a new one."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice"
     :code "(audio/play (quote kick-drum))"
     :note "Trigger the kick-drum sound. In REPL: returns (pending-audio #<object>) — the shape the host would consume.")
    (:tier "apprentice"
     :code "(let ((handle (audio/play (quote background-music)))) (car handle))"
     :note "Save the handle for later halting; the first element is the status tag. Returns pending-audio in REPL.")
    (:tier "intermediate"
     :code "(map audio/play (list (quote hit1) (quote hit2) (quote hit3)))"
     :note "Trigger three sounds in sequence and collect the handles. Under a live host they all play; in REPL you get three pending-audio pairs.")
    (:tier "expert"
     :code "(define (loop-music track) (let ((h (audio/play track))) (if (and (pair? h) (symbol? (car h)) (equal? (symbol->string (car h)) \"pending-audio\")) (list (quote will-play-when-ready) track) (list (quote playing) track)))) (loop-music (quote ambient))"
     :note "Branch on the status tag: 'will-play-when-ready if headless, 'playing if the live host reported success. Uses symbol->string because the returned tag is a Sym.")
    (:tier "master"
     :code "(let* ((tracks (list (quote lofi) (quote jazz) (quote synth))) (handles (map audio/play tracks))) (list (quote tracks) (length tracks) (quote handles) (length handles)))"
     :note "Fan out a playlist: fire off three tracks, save all three handles, report the counts. Real carts extend this to schedule crossfades between the tracks.")
  )
  :caveats
    ("Handles are opaque; do not try to read them beyond passing to audio/halt."
     "Multiple plays layer, they do not replace. Halt the old handle first if you want a swap."
     "Comparing the head to 'pending-audio via `equal?` fails because Sym identity differs; use `symbol->string` or `symbol-name` if you need a string match."
     "Resource must exist in the pre-loaded cache under a live host; unknown resources fail silently in REPL.")
  :drawbacks
    ("No built-in fade-in — combine with `audio/master-volume` ramping."
     "Long-lived loops accumulate memory if never halted."
     "No priority or voice-stealing — heavy calls can glitch the audio thread.")
  :usecases
    ("Trigger a sound effect on button press."
     "Start a looping music bed at cart open."
     "Layer ambient tracks with a per-source volume."
     "Play a UI feedback ping on state transitions.")
  :related ("audio/halt" "audio/master-volume" "audio/playing?" "note/strike" "synth/play")
  :learn
    (:concept "Handle-returning verbs — save the return, pass it to halt when done."
     :prerequisites ("(core)/let" "audio/halt")
     :progression "Start with a single audio/play + audio/halt bracket. Then fan out multiple tracks. Then build a crossfade helper.")

  :+eng
    (:impl-file "src/wired-verbs.js"
     :impl-notes "wired-verbs.js:404. Returns [pending-audio {source opts}] in REPL. Host surfaces override with a real Web Audio buffer-source launcher."
     :permission "state-change"
     :latency-class "async-quick"
     :tests "REPL-verified by Yuki 2026-07-14: novice=(pending-audio #<object>); apprentice=pending-audio; intermediate=(3 pairs); expert=(will-play-when-ready ambient); master=(tracks 3 handles 3)."
     :since "1.0")

  :+ai
    (:raises ()
     :pipes-into ("audio/halt")
     :cardinality one
     :deterministic #f
     :cacheable #f
     :common-mistakes "Assuming audio/play restarts a running stream — it layers. Comparing the return's head via `equal?` on a literal quote — Sym identity fails; use symbol->string."
     :when-not-to-use "You want simple bell-clean pitches — use `note/strike`. You want a rich synthesized voice — use `synth/orch` or `synth/808`. You want to schedule a whole song — use `synth/play` with a score.")

  :+meta
    (:spec-version "1.0"
     :schema-version "1.0"
     :entry-provenance "authored"
     :required-fields-present #t
     :entry-summary "Trigger a sound. Returns a handle for later halting. Descriptor tuple in REPL."))

(verb
  :name "audio/master-volume"
  :library "audio"
  :kind "mut"
  :signature "(audio/master-volume level) -> [ok {level}]"
  :summary "Set the global audio-output gain. Records the intent in cortex; returns [ok info]."
  :impl-status "wired-partial"
  :explanation "audio/master-volume is one of the few audio verbs with a small real side effect in the standalone REPL: it stores the requested level in cortex under the key 'audio/master-volume' so subsequent (cortex/read 'audio/master-volume) recovers it. The return is [ok {level}] — the same shape a live host uses. Level is a number, conventionally in [0, 1] but clamping is host-specific. Multiple calls in one frame all record; the last one wins. Combine with a step-loop to build a fade."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice"
     :code "(audio/master-volume 0.5)"
     :note "Set volume to 0.5. Returns (ok #<object>). The 0.5 is recorded in cortex so it survives across REPL frames.")
    (:tier "apprentice"
     :code "(begin (audio/master-volume 1) (audio/master-volume 0.5))"
     :note "Two calls; the second wins. Under a live host the gain node's value settles at 0.5.")
    (:tier "intermediate"
     :code "(map audio/master-volume (list 0 0.25 0.5 0.75 1))"
     :note "Sweep across five levels in one map. Returns five [ok ...] pairs — one per call.")
    (:tier "expert"
     :code "(define (fade steps) (let loop ((i 0)) (if (>= i steps) (quote faded) (begin (audio/master-volume (- 1 (/ i steps))) (loop (+ i 1)))))) (fade 5)"
     :note "A simple linear fade-out over N steps. Under a live host the sound audibly ramps; in REPL the intent is recorded step by step.")
    (:tier "master"
     :code "(let* ((slider 60) (v (/ slider 100))) (audio/master-volume v))"
     :note "Bridge a UI slider (0-100) to the [0, 1] master volume convention. This is what a real settings card does when the user drags the volume knob.")
  )
  :caveats
    ("Level is a number; symbols and strings are not auto-coerced."
     "The convention is [0, 1]; values outside may be clamped by the live host but are still recorded honestly."
     "Global — no per-source volume via this verb. Use per-source rate/volume opts on audio/play instead."
     "Recorded in cortex; you can read the last-set value with (cortex/read 'audio/master-volume).")
  :drawbacks
    ("No fade curve built in; you must orchestrate steps."
     "No query verb specifically for master volume; the recorded key is a workaround.")
  :usecases
    ("Wire a volume slider in a UI card."
     "Build a fade-out helper for scene transitions."
     "Duck the mix when a foreground alert fires."
     "Remember the user's preferred volume across sessions via cortex.")
  :related ("audio/play" "audio/halt" "cortex/read" "radio/volume" "synth/play")
  :learn
    (:concept "Global gain control with intent-recording; the pattern of pairing a live-side effect with a cortex breadcrumb."
     :prerequisites ("(core)/let" "cortex/read")
     :progression "Set the master. Then build a fade loop. Then bridge a slider. Then remember the user's preference across sessions.")

  :+eng
    (:impl-file "src/wired-verbs.js"
     :impl-notes "wired-verbs.js:398-403. Coerces level to a number, stores it in cortex under key 'audio/master-volume', returns [ok {level}]."
     :permission "state-change"
     :latency-class "sync-fast"
     :tests "REPL-verified by Yuki 2026-07-14: novice=(ok #<object>); apprentice=(ok #<object>) after last call; intermediate=5 (ok ...) pairs; expert='faded; master=(ok #<object>)."
     :since "1.0")

  :+ai
    (:raises ()
     :pipes-into ("audio/play" "audio/halt")
     :consumes-from ("UI sliders" "settings state")
     :cardinality one
     :deterministic #t
     :cacheable #t
     :common-mistakes "Passing an integer like 50 expecting percent — the convention is [0, 1]. Combine with a divide (/ slider 100) to bridge."
     :when-not-to-use "You want per-source volume — use audio/play's :volume opt. You want a fade curve — build it out of steps yourself.")

  :+meta
    (:spec-version "1.0"
     :schema-version "1.0"
     :entry-provenance "authored"
     :required-fields-present #t
     :entry-summary "Set global gain. Small side effect: records intent in cortex. [ok info] return."))

(verb
  :name "audio/spectrum"
  :library "audio"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(audio/spectrum) -> [number ...] | descriptor"
  :summary "Read the current FFT band values from the live analyser; a snapshot list of amplitudes per band."
  :impl-status "wired-descriptor"
  :explanation "audio/spectrum returns the current FFT (fast Fourier transform) band values from the live audio analyser — a flat list of numbers, one per frequency band, each in some analyser-normalised range. Under a live host it's the material for visualisers, EQ meters, and music-reactive animations. In the standalone REPL there is no live analyser, so the verb returns the descriptor ('audio/spectrum). Callers should check with `pair?` and treat the descriptor as an empty spectrum. audio/listen must have returned 'ok under a live host before spectrum values are meaningful."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice"
     :code "(audio/spectrum)"
     :note "Snapshot the current FFT. In REPL: returns (\"audio/spectrum\"), a descriptor; under a live host: a list of numbers.")
    (:tier "apprentice"
     :code "(let ((s (audio/spectrum))) (if (pair? s) (quote descriptor) (length s)))"
     :note "Guard on shape: descriptor vs live list. Returns 'descriptor in REPL.")
    (:tier "intermediate"
     :code "(map (lambda (_) (audio/spectrum)) (list 1 2))"
     :note "Poll twice. Safe to call every frame — the verb is read-only. Returns two descriptor copies in REPL.")
    (:tier "expert"
     :code "(define (draw-bars s) (if (pair? s) (list (quote no-spectrum-in-repl)) (map (lambda (b) (* b 10)) s))) (draw-bars (audio/spectrum))"
     :note "A safe consumer: if the spectrum is a descriptor, fall through with a marker; otherwise scale each band. Returns (no-spectrum-in-repl) here.")
    (:tier "master"
     :code "(let loop ((n 0) (acc (list))) (if (>= n 3) (list (quote polled) (length acc) (quote times)) (loop (+ n 1) (cons (audio/spectrum) acc))))"
     :note "Poll three times and accumulate the snapshots — the shape of a rolling-history buffer for a visualiser. Returns (polled 3 times).")
  )
  :caveats
    ("Requires audio/listen == 'ok under a live host; without it, the spectrum is either descriptor or all-zero."
     "Band count is analyser-configured; do not hardcode a length."
     "Values are normalised by the analyser; ranges vary across hosts.")
  :drawbacks
    ("Read-only snapshot; you cannot request specific bands or windows."
     "No smoothing built in; consecutive snapshots may jitter — apply your own low-pass.")
  :usecases
    ("Drive a bar-graph visualiser."
     "Compute band energy for a music-reactive effect."
     "Detect specific frequency-range activity (e.g. bass hits).")
  :related ("audio/listen" "audio/onset?" "audio/onset-strength" "audio/tempo" "audio/key")
  :learn
    (:concept "Frame-rate reading of live FFT data; how to consume a variable-shape return safely."
     :prerequisites ("audio/listen" "(core)/pair?")
     :progression "Read audio/spectrum once. Then poll. Then smooth. Then build a visualiser.")

  :+eng
    (:impl-file "src/reference-impls.js"
     :impl-notes "reference-impls.js:1479-1483. Returns ('audio/spectrum) descriptor in REPL. Host overrides with a real Web Audio AnalyserNode.getByteFrequencyData reader."
     :permission "read-only"
     :latency-class "sync-fast"
     :tests "REPL-verified by Yuki 2026-07-14: novice=('audio/spectrum); apprentice='descriptor; intermediate=(2 copies); expert=(no-spectrum-in-repl); master=(polled 3 times)."
     :since "1.0")

  :+ai
    (:raises ()
     :pipes-into ("audio/onset?" "audio/lufs")
     :consumes-from ("audio/listen")
     :cardinality one
     :deterministic #f
     :cacheable #f
     :common-mistakes "Hardcoding a band count. Skipping audio/listen and expecting real values."
     :when-not-to-use "You need a single loudness number — use audio/lufs. You need an event trigger — use audio/onset?.")

  :+meta
    (:spec-version "1.0"
     :schema-version "1.0"
     :entry-provenance "authored"
     :required-fields-present #t
     :entry-summary "FFT band snapshot. Live: list of numbers. REPL: descriptor."))

(verb
  :name "audio/tempo"
  :library "audio"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(audio/tempo) -> number | descriptor"
  :summary "Read the analyser's current estimate of the audio's tempo in beats per minute."
  :impl-status "wired-descriptor"
  :explanation "audio/tempo asks the live analyser for its current best guess of the tempo of whatever is playing. Under a live host it returns a number in BPM (typically 60-180 for music). In the headless REPL there is no live analyser, so it returns the descriptor ('audio/tempo). Callers should type-check the return with `number?` before using it, or fall through to a default. audio/listen must have returned 'ok under a live host for this to be meaningful."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice"
     :code "(audio/tempo)"
     :note "Query the tempo. In REPL: returns (\"audio/tempo\"), a descriptor.")
    (:tier "apprentice"
     :code "(let ((t (audio/tempo))) (if (pair? t) (quote descriptor) (if (number? t) t (quote unknown))))"
     :note "Distinguish descriptor / number / other. Returns 'descriptor in REPL.")
    (:tier "intermediate"
     :code "(map (lambda (_) (audio/tempo)) (list 1 2))"
     :note "Two polls of the tempo. Read-only and idempotent.")
    (:tier "expert"
     :code "(define (tempo-bin) (let ((t (audio/tempo))) (cond ((pair? t) (quote unknown)) ((< t 90) (quote slow)) ((< t 130) (quote medium)) (else (quote fast))))) (tempo-bin)"
     :note "Bin the tempo into slow/medium/fast. Returns 'unknown in REPL because the descriptor is a pair.")
    (:tier "master"
     :code "(let* ((probes (list 1 2 3 4)) (readings (map (lambda (_) (audio/tempo)) probes))) (list (quote readings) (length readings)))"
     :note "Sample the tempo four times — the shape of a rolling-tempo estimator that averages several probes.")
  )
  :caveats
    ("Requires audio/listen 'ok under a live host."
     "Estimate — not exact. May jitter or lag by a bar."
     "Genre-dependent: complex rhythms may yield unstable estimates.")
  :drawbacks
    ("No confidence value returned; a wild guess and a solid one look the same."
     "Cannot request per-track tempo — global aggregate.")
  :usecases
    ("Sync visuals to the beat via bpm-aware pacing."
     "Bin tempo for a genre classifier."
     "Choose an appropriate fill or transition for the current beat.")
  :related ("audio/listen" "audio/onset?" "audio/bar-clock" "audio/key")
  :learn
    (:concept "Live tempo estimation and how to consume it safely."
     :prerequisites ("audio/listen" "(core)/cond")
     :progression "Read audio/tempo. Then bin it. Then use audio/bar-clock to advance visuals per bar.")

  :+eng
    (:impl-file "src/reference-impls.js"
     :impl-notes "reference-impls.js:1479-1483. Returns ('audio/tempo) descriptor. Host binds to a real tempo detector."
     :permission "read-only"
     :latency-class "sync-fast"
     :tests "REPL-verified 2026-07-14: novice=('audio/tempo); apprentice='descriptor; intermediate=2 copies; expert='unknown; master=(readings 4)."
     :since "1.0")

  :+ai
    (:raises ()
     :pipes-into ("audio/bar-clock")
     :consumes-from ("audio/listen")
     :cardinality one
     :deterministic #f
     :cacheable #f
     :common-mistakes "Treating the descriptor as a number. Believing the estimate is exact — it can wobble by 3-5 BPM."
     :when-not-to-use "You want an exact bar clock — use audio/bar-clock instead.")

  :+meta
    (:spec-version "1.0"
     :schema-version "1.0"
     :entry-provenance "authored"
     :required-fields-present #t
     :entry-summary "Tempo estimate in BPM. Descriptor return in REPL."))

(verb
  :name "audio/key"
  :library "audio"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(audio/key) -> [string string number] | #f | descriptor"
  :summary "Read the analyser's current best guess of the musical key (root, mode, confidence)."
  :impl-status "wired-descriptor"
  :explanation "audio/key returns a three-element tuple: (root mode confidence) where root is a pitch string like \"C\" or \"F#\", mode is \"major\" or \"minor\", and confidence is a number in [0, 1]. Under a live host with warm analyser this reflects the detected key. If no key is currently detectable the host returns #f. In headless REPL there is no live analyser, so the verb returns the descriptor ('audio/key). Callers should check with `pair?` first, then either use the descriptor as a marker or extract car/cadr/caddr from the tuple."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice"
     :code "(audio/key)"
     :note "Query the current key. In REPL: returns (\"audio/key\") — a descriptor.")
    (:tier "apprentice"
     :code "(let ((k (audio/key))) (if (pair? k) (car k) k))"
     :note "Extract the head. In REPL the head is the verb-name string.")
    (:tier "intermediate"
     :code "(if (pair? (audio/key)) (quote no-key-in-repl) (audio/key))"
     :note "Guard on descriptor shape; fall through to a symbolic marker.")
    (:tier "expert"
     :code "(define (mode-color) (let ((k (audio/key))) (cond ((pair? k) (quote gray)) ((null? k) (quote none)) ((and (pair? k) (>= (length k) 2) (equal? (cadr k) \"major\")) (quote warm)) (else (quote cool))))) (mode-color)"
     :note "Palette by mode: 'gray if no live key, 'warm for major, 'cool for minor. Returns 'gray in REPL.")
    (:tier "master"
     :code "(let loop ((n 0) (last (quote none))) (if (>= n 2) (list (quote after) n (quote polls) (quote last) last) (loop (+ n 1) (audio/key))))"
     :note "Poll audio/key twice, save the last observation. Under a live host this stabilises the reading; in REPL you accumulate the descriptor.")
  )
  :caveats
    ("Returned as a tuple under live host; descriptor in REPL. Check with pair? first."
     "Confidence is (0, 1]; low values mean the key detector is guessing."
     "Enharmonic equivalents may collapse (\"Cs\" vs \"Db\") depending on the analyser.")
  :drawbacks
    ("Global aggregate; no per-track key."
     "Slow to update; a mid-song modulation may lag by several bars.")
  :usecases
    ("Colour a palette by detected mode."
     "Show the current key in a music-theory HUD."
     "Guide a real-time accompaniment that must stay in key.")
  :related ("audio/tempo" "audio/spectrum" "audio/listen")
  :learn
    (:concept "Live key detection and safe consumption of a tuple/descriptor union return."
     :prerequisites ("audio/listen" "(core)/pair?" "(core)/cond")
     :progression "Ask audio/key. Then extract root and mode. Then bind to a palette. Then read confidence to fade the effect.")

  :+eng
    (:impl-file "src/reference-impls.js"
     :impl-notes "reference-impls.js:1479-1483. Returns ('audio/key) descriptor. Host binds to a key detector."
     :permission "read-only"
     :latency-class "sync-fast"
     :tests "REPL-verified 2026-07-14: novice=('audio/key); apprentice=\"audio/key\"; intermediate='no-key-in-repl; expert='gray; master=(after 2 polls last ('audio/key))."
     :since "1.0")

  :+ai
    (:raises ()
     :pipes-into ()
     :consumes-from ("audio/listen")
     :cardinality one
     :deterministic #f
     :cacheable #f
     :common-mistakes "Reading (car k) expecting the root string when the return is a descriptor. Assuming enharmonic normalisation."
     :when-not-to-use "You need pitch-level accuracy — this is a coarse root+mode estimate.")

  :+meta
    (:spec-version "1.0"
     :schema-version "1.0"
     :entry-provenance "authored"
     :required-fields-present #t
     :entry-summary "Detected key: (root mode confidence). Descriptor in REPL."))

(verb
  :name "audio/lufs"
  :library "audio"
  :kind "rd"
  :signature "(audio/lufs) -> number | #f | descriptor"
  :summary "Read the analyser's integrated LUFS loudness measurement."
  :impl-status "wired-descriptor"
  :explanation "LUFS (Loudness Units, Full Scale) is a perceptual loudness standard used in broadcast and streaming. Under a live host, audio/lufs returns the integrated loudness over a short (~400ms) window as a number, typically negative (0 = clipping, -Inf = silence). Under headless REPL there is no live analyser, so the verb returns the descriptor ('audio/lufs). Callers use `number?` to distinguish live vs headless. Useful for perceptual gain matching and loudness normalisation."
  :examples (
    (:tier "novice"
     :code "(audio/lufs)"
     :note "Query loudness. In REPL: returns (\"audio/lufs\") — a descriptor.")
    (:tier "apprentice"
     :code "(let ((l (audio/lufs))) (if (number? l) l (quote no-signal)))"
     :note "Return the LUFS number under live host, or 'no-signal in headless. Returns 'no-signal here.")
    (:tier "intermediate"
     :code "(map (lambda (_) (audio/lufs)) (list 1 2 3))"
     :note "Poll three times. LUFS is a windowed integrated measure — consecutive reads may hardly differ.")
    (:tier "expert"
     :code "(define (loudness-tier) (let ((l (audio/lufs))) (cond ((not (number? l)) (quote unknown)) ((< l -30) (quote quiet)) ((< l -18) (quote comfortable)) (else (quote loud))))) (loudness-tier)"
     :note "Bin the loudness into quiet / comfortable / loud. Returns 'unknown in REPL.")
    (:tier "master"
     :code "(let loop ((n 0)) (if (>= n 3) (quote done-polling) (begin (audio/lufs) (loop (+ n 1)))))"
     :note "Sample-poll three times. The shape of a rolling-loudness estimator that averages several probes for stability.")
  )
  :caveats
    ("Integrated measure — instantaneous peaks are NOT captured. Use audio/spectrum + audio/onset-strength for transients."
     "Requires audio/listen 'ok under a live host."
     "Values are unbounded below; approaching -Inf for silence.")
  :drawbacks
    ("~400ms window lags real-time changes. Do not rely on it for sub-frame triggers."
     "Adds cost — requires a warm analyser + integration buffer.")
  :usecases
    ("Adaptive gain: match perceived loudness across sources."
     "Loudness meter in a mixing UI."
     "Broadcast/podcast normalisation to -16 or -14 LUFS.")
  :related ("audio/listen" "audio/spectrum" "audio/master-volume" "audio/tempo")
  :learn
    (:concept "Perceptual loudness — LUFS as a psychoacoustic measure — versus raw dBFS."
     :prerequisites ("audio/listen")
     :progression "Read audio/lufs. Then compute a target-difference. Then apply as an audio/master-volume gain change.")

  :+eng
